ome characteristic forenames:  French Jacques, Etienne, Yvrose.","English (Cornwall): variant of   Mitchell   and   Michel  .","German: variant of   Michel  . This surname is rare in Germany."]},{"name":"Mutch","meanings":["Scottish (Aberdeenshire) and English (Lancashire and Cheshire): nickname for a large (tall or fat) person, from Middle English <i>moche</i>, <i>muche</i> ‘big’ (a shortened form of <i>mochel</i>, <i>muchel</i>). Compare   Mitchell  ,   Meikle  , and   Muckle  ."]},{"name":"Meikle","meanings":["Scottish: nickname from Middle Scots <i>mekill</i>, <i>meikill</i> ‘big’. Compare   Mitchell   2,   Muckle  , and   Mutch  ."]},{"name":"Mickle","meanings":["English (Northumberland): nickname from Middle English <i>mikel</i>, <i>mekel</i>, <i>mukel</i> ‘big’. Compare   Mitchell  ,   Meikle  , and   Mutch  .","Americanized form of German   Mickel   1 or of a homonymous Germanized Sorbian surname (see   Mickel   2)."]},{"name":"Michael","meanings":["English, German, Dutch, Jewish, and Greek: from the personal name <i>Michael</i>, ultimately from Hebrew <i>Mika’el</i> ‘Who is like God?’. This was borne by an archangel in the Bible, the protector of Israel (Daniel 10:13, 12:1; Rev. 12:7). In Christian tradition, Michael was regarded as the warrior archangel, conqueror of Satan, and the personal name was correspondingly popular throughout Europe, especially in knightly and military families. In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed many cognates from other languages, e.g. Hungarian <b>Mihály</b> (see   Mihaly  ), Czech and Slovak   Michal  , Assyrian/Chaldean or Arabic   Mikhael   and   Mikhail  , and also patronymics and other derivatives from these names, e.g. Greek   Papamichael  , its cognate <b>Papamichalis</b>, and   Michaelides  , Serbian <b>Mihajlović</b> (see   Mihajlovic  ), and Slovenian <b>Mihelčič</b> (see   Mihelcic  ). Compare   Mikeal  ."]},{"name":"Mitchel","meanings":["English: variant of   Mitchell  ."]},{"name":"Mixell","meanings":["Scottish and English: variant of   Mitchell  ."]},{"name":"Muckle","meanings":["English (Northumberland): nickname for a big man, from Middle English <i>mikel</i>, <i>mekel</i>, <i>mukel</i> ‘big’ (Old English <i>mycel</i>). Compare   Mitchell  ,   Meikle   and   Mutch  .","South German: from a diminutive of   Muck   ‘gnat’."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When John Mitchell was born about 1348, in England, United Kingdom, his father, John Mitchell, was 22 and his mother, Margaret Matham, was 21. He married Clemency Gilbert about 1359, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died after 1359."},"et":{"about 1348–after 1359":"umbes 1348–pärast 1359","1348–1359":"1348–1359","1340–Female":"1340–Surnud","1360–1444":"1360–1444","1328–Male":"1328–Surnud","1328–Female":"1328–Surnud","1359":"1359","1348":"1348","after 1359":"pärast 1359","1444":"1444","about 1347":"umbes 1347","about 1348":"umbes 1348","about 1359":"umbes 1359","1340":"1340","1360":"1360","1328":"1328","England":"England","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Penhurst, Sussex, England":"Penhurst, Sussex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1348–after 1359":"noin 1348–1359 jälkeen","1348–1359":"1348–1359","1340–Female":"1340–Kuollut","1360–1444":"1360–1444","1328–Male":"1328–Kuollut","1328–Female":"1328–Kuollut","1359":"1359","1348":"1348","after 1359":"1359 jälkeen","1444":"1444","about 1347":"noin 1347","about 1348":"noin 1348","about 1359":"noin 1359","1340":"1340","1360":"1360","1328":"1328","England":"England","England, United Kingdom":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Penhurst, Sussex, England":"Penhurst, Sussex, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"about 1348–after 1359":"environ 1348–après 1359","1348–1359":"1348–1359","1340–Female":"1340–Décédée